Are you sure the answer for `arr = [5, 7, 9, 4, 11]` would be `9`? Adding 6 to 4 gives the required result `[5, 7, 9, 10, 11]`.
Find both, additions to make array increasing as well as decreasing and return minimum.
For ascending,[1] a forward traversal maintaining maximum till then assigning 1 more than maximum to those out of order gives the first value. A backward traversal performing similar steps as [1]  gives us the other value.
Java code:
```
private static long solution(int[] arr)
{
    long asc = 0L, desc = 0L;
    int max = -1;
    for(int i : arr)
    {
        if(i <= max)
        {
            asc += (max-i+1);
            max++;
        }
        max = Math.max(max,i);
    }
    max = -1;
    for(int i = arr.length-1; i >= 0; i--)
    {
        if(arr[i] <= max)
        {
            desc += (max-arr[i]+1);
            max ++;
        }
        max = Math.max(max,arr[i]);
    }
    return Math.min(asc,desc);
}
```

